Below is an example HTML file that includes both a buggy version and a corrected version of a visual counter widget. The buggy version demonstrates a race condition when rapidly clicking the button, while the corrected version resolves the issue.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Race Condition Demo</title>
    <style>
        .container {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
        }
        .version {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .explanation {
            font-size: 14px;
            color: gray;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="version">
            <h2>Buggy Version</h2>
            <p>Count: <span id="buggy-count">0</span></p>
            <button onclick="buggyIncrement()">Increment</button>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p>The race condition occurs because multiple asynchronous updates using <code>setTimeout</code> can overlap, reading the shared <code>count</code> variable before the previous update has a chance to write the new value.</p>
                <p>For example, if the user clicks the button rapidly:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Read <code>count = 0</code></li>
                    <li>Before writing <code>count = 1</code>, the user clicks the button again:</li>
                    <li>Read <code>count = 0</code> (not <code>count = 1</code> because the write hasn't happened yet)</li>
                    <li>Write <code>count = 1</code> (first click)</li>
                    <li>Write <code>count = 1</code> (second click)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>This results in the displayed count falling behind or showing wrong values.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="version">
            <h2>Corrected Version</h2>
            <p>Count: <span id="corrected-count">0</span></p>
            <button onclick="correctedIncrement()">Increment</button>
            <div class="explanation">
                <p>The fix resolves the race condition by ensuring that updates to the <code>count</code> variable are sequential, using a technique called "cancellation and re-queueing" or by directly updating the DOM without a shared variable.</p>
                <p>In this corrected version, we directly update the DOM without a shared variable:</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        let buggyCount = 0;
        function buggyIncrement() {
            setTimeout(() => {
                buggyCount++;
                document.getElementById('buggy-count').textContent = buggyCount;
            }, 0);
        }

        function correctedIncrement() {
            const countElement = document.getElementById('corrected-count');
            const currentCount = parseInt(countElement.textContent);
            countElement.textContent = currentCount + 1;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In the buggy version, the `buggyIncrement` function demonstrates the race condition by using `setTimeout` to asynchronously update the shared `buggyCount` variable. When rapidly clicking the button, overlapping updates can cause the displayed count to fall behind or show wrong values.

The corrected version resolves the issue by directly updating the DOM without a shared variable in the `correctedIncrement` function. This approach ensures that updates to the count are sequential and accurate, even with rapid button clicks.

